76561197993623864,Recommended,265590,16997143,"Posted: 11 July, 2015",all,TheButterKnife,"For anyone who missed something anywhere near the lines of Alien Swarm, this is something that at least hits the lines of ""Similar."" Meaning that this is a highly team based overhead style game where classes actually seem to matter with a sickening amount of fine tuning options available to each of the eight classes.Up to eight players are allowed in a game, though there are specific limitations on how many instances of each class allowed typically either 4, (Assault) 2, (Heavy Support, Medics, etc) or only 1 (Hellfires, Terminators, Etc.) Though as there isn't a infinite ammunition system and a toss mag reload (Meaning anything left in the magazine when reloaded is ""Tossed"" or simply lost.) ammunition can quickly become sparse.The voice acting in the single player game is terrible and it feels, clunky especially in the beggining levels, so I spent most of my time on multiplayer scenarios.Upon which comes my biggest lament with the game. Characters are allowed two weapons, a primary weapon and a secondary. Of the secondary weapons available there is a handgun or pistol. For whatever reason this uses primary weapon ammunition regardless of if it happens to be napalm, full metal jacket, or hollowpoint. Which renders it's overall effectiveness somewhat questionable compared to a grenade launcher, Rocket launcher, or even shotgun which use their own ammunition pool and have vast room clearing capacities compared to a pistol.Granted, a Hellfire can replenish their GAR (Gauss Assault Rifle) from a fuel barrel in this so maybe the point is moot...If one enjoyes wave/endless monsters trying to claw their jibblies while trying to complete objectives in a story-esque fashion and all the chaos involved with it, especially with up to eight friends... then your likely going to sink much more time into this than you had origionally planned. The mechanics of the game are good (With the occasional wall where explosives may pass through) the only failing point so far is to make a truly engaging story singleplayer. Having a bad voice acter (Think like a B movie commando that can no where near sell it or a solid snake impersonator) whom the player is FORCED to listen to quickly ruins any immersion and saps the will to continue.My reccomendation is to play it how it seems to be meant to. As multiplayer. Grab your guns, and your comrades, and never stop firing, otherwise your going to be picking claws out of your backside."
76561197963664525,Recommended,265590,17037104,"Posted: 13 July, 2015",all,Terkala,"Few games do multiplayer co-op well without requiring you to have a friend to play with. This game is great for just hop-in, play a while, and not need to make a big production out of gathering up your friends."
76561198171808873,Recommended,265590,26366858,"Posted: 1 November, 2016",all,sla_sla10,"Don't get discouraged by reviews of people who get frustrated by dying early. This is a game that doesn't hold your hand, has a complex system and has quite a learning curve. it is advised for new squads to do easy difficulty first to familiarize. It shines on multiplayer but you have to do your due diligence (i.e. Go through single player, familiarize with items etc.) This game is not about grinding through the ranks. A team of 8 who knows the game  can create new accounts and beat the game while they're all at rank 1. It's about teamwork, respecting the enemies (why most new players die is they don't respect the swarm), achieving goals as a team, and playing your role (as medic, tank, dps/carry, utility, scout, forward observer etc.).  If you are a fan of the old top down squad games like Night of the Dead, Undead Assault and its ilk, this game is for you. If you want a challenging/complex game that requires teamwork and has hero-based system, you'll like this game.CONS:- Single player can only give you 10 to 20 hours of fun. Most of the fun is in multiplayer.- Only a few maps to go through. I believe the devs can create a random map generator. There is a tactical advantage though of knowing the map.- high difficulty. This is a team game. If the healer doesn't know what to do, or the tank, then the squad will most likely fall. There is a need for a good leader at higher difficulties.- medium to steep learning curve, depending on how good you want to be.- if you die early, you will be automatically revived if you are new to the game. However, after a few ranks, there will no longer be an automatic revive. A medic or a mission can revive you, but you will have to wait.PROS- Team game. I've played with Europeans, Chinese, Canadians and Americans. A good world we are in. At higher difficulties, you need to talk, so teamspeak would be necessary. There's a different sense of achievement when you defeat a game as a team.- Hero-based system. You control one character, customize it and change its load out. There are 8 classes that each have a role to play. Mastery of a class is a journey and there are different ways to build a single class.- Squadron tactics. You have an enemy sniper shooting at 124m away while a swarm is constantly flowing to your team, what do you do? 3 big fatties chasing you? Fast dogs gnawing at one of your team? Some military squad tactics apply, like leapfrog movements, defensive positions, buddy system etc. The squad leaer has a large impact and responsibility.- Random missions and enemies. Every game is different depending on the mission, the boss spawn etc."
76561198000917255,Not Recommended,265590,30409241,Posted: 9 March,all,Range Killer,"There is alot to like about this game, but I'm not sure the bad outweigh the good.  Some of the biggest problems are the controls, game difficulty, and the beta state of the game.The controls are an absolute pain.  You will constantly default to the team leader when you change control modes.  Autofire will turn on when you select another team member.  Sometimes your team will follow you, sometimes the game will toggle off autofollow.  Sometimes you will put out a squad in tactical mode, then the team will assemble on the leader immediatly on leaving the mode.  All these things feel intentional, however and only make the game feel clunky by design.  Other games might get away with it but as frantic as the later levels can get, you will see your team wipe due to this.I laughed when I saw a note at the start of one level, saying the waves of enemies are NOT endless.  They did feel endless at many points, and that indicates the difficulty.  Too much is not explained, or poorly explained in the game.  Some levels are purely trial and error.  Save points are fairly far between.  At first the game comes across as a frantic, tactical game.  After a few levels it feels like a forced rush to finsh quickly.  Some levels you can slow down and think it out, others you have a set path to victory that is explained in no way, except dont die.So much is odd about this game.  The skill discriptions that say ""Discription Not Found"".  The story explained in a text block in the options.  No idea how to gain experience.  I found a few guides that said you gained experience from looting lockers (???).  Alot of this feels like new ideas, and if it was explained in some way I'd give the devs the benefit of the doubt, but it feels lazy and half finished.  Also, I will mention the hoops you need to jump through to get it to run is staggering.  I spent a few days trying to get it to run, just to give up in frustration.  6 months later I tried on a new PC, and it started up without a hitch.The game has some really cool moments and is addictive to a point.  That point is when you realize its nearly broken in difficulty at certain points.  I'm not really sure the game is worth the purchase price, whatever it is, considering its a dice roll to get it to run.  If you enjoy zombie games, and tactical shooters, it might be worth a look."
