,Recommended,265590,11842687,"Posted: 23 August, 2014",all,Skankles,"It’s been two years, so I figured I’d take another crack at what there is to say about The Red Solstice…This kickstarter game, birthed from Starcraft and Warcraft mods, NOTD or Night Of The Dead has come a long way. It's a top down, action based, strategy, horror, survival game, where you control a single soldier, in a group of 1-8 players fighting against waves of monstrous AI controlled enemies. There are options to play with a player controlled team of 3 semi-intelligent marines, but the meat of the game comes from the live co-op play. Over the past few months of playing, I can clearly see that the game has gotten a lot better. I’ve tried to touch on the major categories that I personally feel like need to be addressed in this follow up review of the game, specifically the balance, the community, the controls, and the content. This review is critical and doesn’t cover all of the better points of the game, but addresses many of the issues that were the major detractors of the game upon my first review.BALANCEThe difficulty rankings have four stages from an easy mode for new players,to the bleeding edge hard mode for those who have sunk in well over 200 hours of gameplay with maxed out suits. The game balancing has been tweaked to make playing the game reasonable at entry level, but maintains a challenge into the harder modes. Regardless, without a solid team, the chance of survival on normal (soldier) difficulty is still pretty low. The learning curve in the game is steep!  Developing 'run away skills' and learning from tactical errors (death), comes with time - more objectives completed, enemies killed and a successfully evac results in appropriate bonuses. There are no dead weight classes once you become proficient, which is nice to see as well. Some vets and more experienced players may try to build specific teams to their meta, but there are no classes that are never worth taking, which brings me to my next topic.COMMUNITYThis really needs to be addressed based on the very small player base of this game. There are a few great players that are helpful, nice and can make the game great to play. Without naming any names, there was one community member with over a thousand hours who found me when I re-joined the game and was very forward in wanting to provide a positive experience coming back into the game. I have seen a select few work towards raising up new players and helping them with their suit builds and laying out a plan in game to win. They lead by example and remain positive providing a genuinely high quality experience. That being said, some people are cancer. A few veteran players in particular are unchecked malignant growths that have been hanging on for far too long. One example in particular, let’s call him “Lord D-Bag” intentionally fragged a team member without warning because he believed that the team member wasn’t playing to Lord D-Bag’s chosen meta. What followed was a verbal fight and unapologetically run the team into the ground ending in a team loss.This behavior is unacceptable. Veteran players who dictate instead of leading has been a serious problem with the game since the game’s inception. I was happy to see a few friends who I used to play with re-join to have players like Lord D-Bag rudely talk down to them without insight, resulting in a lost player. This mentality of “my house, my rules” has created a small player base, and has limited the game since it's inception. I have to say, fortunately, that these players are now in the minority, but it is something to be aware of and to avoid. If you’ve ever played a game online late in the life cycle, none of this is new, but remember!: Positivity breeds positivity.CONTROLSI tell people, whenever I try to explain this game, that TRS is very reminiscent of StarCraft. It’s like taking a Terran Marine and stripping away all of the base building and having a lone marine weather the Zerg. For those who don’t understand the reference, it’s a game of precision. Many slight movements with precise clicks can make all of the difference. A self induced death is just as easy as getting killed by an enemy with a poorly placed explosive, or a missed healing. The skill hotkeys and team movement commands are straightforward. The issues come from the crappy hotkeys for the game items in your character's inventory and trying to control an AI team. When things get heated, you don’t want to accidentally hit the wrong hotkey combination and deploy a tactical nuke instead of a medkit, and it’s startlingly easy to do. This leads to having to click in the inventory to use every item. That’s not the worst thing, but it’s far from convenient. When it comes to controlling AI when you’re playing a solo game, the controls are the same as setting guidelines for a team in multiplayer. You can press the spacebar to go into a “tactical mode” which slows down time and allows you to click on the other character’s banner to directly control them like you would your own character. The problem comes from trying to control the other semi-AI characters when you have another player. The standard controls completely change for whatever reason. Without getting into the details of all of the flaws, let's just say the semi-AI requires a lot of micromanagement, with the memory of a goldfish and no tactical mode to help sort it out. This is exceptionally difficult to manage when you’re in the heat of battle and you need to precision to stay alive. This underlines the requirement playing multiplayer with people ONLY, or singleplayer survival with the AI team ONLY. Difficult.CONTENTThe amount of content in the game has increased quite a bit in the past few years. Now it has a story driven single-player mode which is focused on plot events leading up to the story of the multiplayer mode. After a single pass on story mode, (which is all you’ll want to do) the game will boil down to its multi-player focus. There are a decent number of maps to play on, which are decently well designed and balanced with their own individual perks and difficulties. There are a lot of customizable multiplayer modes including defending a bunker, killing insurgents, collecting data entries, destroying alien pods and others, with additional modifiers. All of these come  on the back of a waved survival mode. There are also a hand full of different suits your character can wear including a few stand outs like a marksman who has a extremely potent rail gun, a heavily armed demolition class, energy weapon / teleportation specialist terminator and others. They are all unique and have their own perks and uses, though some skills feel underpowered while others are must haves. As stated in the community portion, some players will tell you to change if they find that your build isn't what they want, but in the end, it’s all based on how you like to play, and there are plenty of options to cater to your whim.CONCLUSIONThough this game has some flaws, I personally enjoy the game. I've put in 360+ hours at the time of this review, over 150 more since my first. At this time I’ve maxed out all of my suits abilities and am able to reach the final wave of survival by myself, but I still haven’t maxed out my maximum proficiency (rank). I still have awards to win and higher goals to conquer. As a new player, online guides are available to help get you started, and there are helpful players who can get you proficient in no time. It’s also nice to see that the developers are still on board, hosting Tournaments and keeping the community live! I am happy to recommend this game to my friends and get them engaged. I think it would be great to bring in new players and breathe some new life into this game."
