76561198005406191,Not Recommended,265590,34956651,Posted: 14 September,all,servvsumbrarum,"Greetings Everyone!  Today I will be reviewing The Red Solstice; I bought this game way back when it was in early access because I liked the idea of a hardcore tactical shooter with RPG mechanics.  The Early Access was very promising, bugs and all and now I’m back to see what they’ve done with it upon completion!Let’s just tack this on:  One of the additions since I last played was the singleplayer campaign.  I was very excited as I love squad based tactical rpgs (Aarklash is my highest recommendation) but was almost immediately disappointed how they implemented it.  You can only directly control the squad leader without using the tactical view which is nice as it slows the game down by 90% but what if I want to directly control the medic or don’t want to but made my commander the medic because I needed one.  This added to the fact that the AI squadmates will do nothing but autofire (which was very annoying during the mission where monsters that couldn’t be auto targeted attacked).  I’m harping on this a lot but the single player feels tacked on, the voice acting is shoddy, half the time turrets don’t work (final mission was annoying as turrets couldn’t be attacked because they were perpetually turning off and on).We’re going to a bug planet:  So many little bugs, I’m not going to say they could be easily fixed but there were programming errors looking up tool tips, I mean really?  The AI squadmates would only half follow you, one time my sniper died because he was stuck on a corner.  When I highlight an ability its range should be displayed (I’m talking to you Heal).  I understand that I could micro better but the games difficulty should be intended, I should be fighting STROL not the game itself.  In addition the game doesn’t seem to remember loadouts mission to mission; yes my medic is going to take life drone…as she always does.  Speaking of healing, medical station bugs out if you die and counts previous uses that you can’t destroy because they aren’t there any more…fun fact.  That was a rage moment of mine.  There are subtitles so that’s good…especially when the music is doing its super stage diving rock out (throw up those horns) right over that stupid story voice acting no one wanted to hear anyway.No one can hear you scream:  The game’s multiplayer is dead…yup, sorry but it is.  This is a great shame as the main bulk of the game is developed around multiplayer.  I spent a few days looking for some life on the multiplayer but no matter what time I tried I didn’t see anyone.  Mars must have been wiped out (to be fair I did find a straggler or two).  I played with some bots (which is a nice attempt but for the previous reasons it leaves a lot to be desired) that they give you that can level and unlock everything for them the same way you would unlock for your own character.  Oh…I forgot to mention, you level, unlock classes and abilities; for the type of gamer I am this multiplayer would have been amazing.  I remember playing the unfinished version of this game in early access and thoroughly enjoying it.  But with the multiplayer dead and the single player beaten (with no interest of going back into that bug pit) I'm forced so uninstall with sad thoughts of what could have been.  I've thought about buying a copy for some friends but a lot of my friends don't really play 'indie' games and would immediately quit a the sight of bad tooltips.Ultimately, if you have 3 friends and all want to get into this game together…hmm, was about to say to buy it but with the bugs and unfinished nature…not sure.  The game left me with a large amount of frustration, not just because it was buggy and incomplete but because there is an amazing game behind all that grit.  I love that they continue the story in multiplayer, love the concept of real time squad combat that has a soul’s genre difficulty.  But this game is infected and it is time to find a new planet to call home."
